 course with an encouraging instructor and enough practice assessments<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9. <a href=\"#anchor-9\">Excel Basics for Data Analysis (IBM)<\/a><\/td>\n<td>12 hours<\/td>\n<td>Clear and concise Excel course on foundational Excel with IBM\u2019s hands-on labs<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10. <a href=\"#anchor-10\">Data Analysis in Excel (DataCamp)<\/a><\/td>\n<td>4 hours<\/td>\n<td>Short Excel class to become industry-ready with free access to the first chapter<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<\/tbody>\n<\/table>\n<\/div>\n<h2>What is Microsoft Excel?<\/h2>\n<p>Microsoft Excel is a popular spreadsheet application developed by Microsoft. It is part of the Microsoft Office suite containing other software like Word, PowerPoint, and Access among others. Not only Windows, Excel can also be run on Android, MacOS, and iOS.<\/p>\n<p>Excel is widely used for performing simple to complex calculations and data visualization (that is creating interactive graphs and charts from your data). It also comes with a built-in programming language called VBA or Visual Basic Applications. VBA is a special programming language you can even use to manipulate data on the spreadsheet which is otherwise difficult to do!<\/p>\n<p>In Excel, data is stored in \u201ccells\u201d formed by the intersection of rows and columns. Like many other spreadsheets, Excel can be used to organize data and perform arithmetic operations. Excel is used in many fields such as science, engineering, finance and simple daily calculations.<\/p>\n<h3>Why are Excel skills important?<\/h3>\n<p>Since Excel has such a wide variety of uses, it\u2019s only natural that it\u2019s a much sought-after skill. According to a <a href=\"https:\/\/assets.publishing.service.gov.uk\/government\/uploads\/system\/uploads\/attachment_data\/file\/807830\/No_Longer_Optional_Employer_Demand_for_Digital_Skills.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">research by the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) of the Government of UK<\/a>, Microsoft Excel is one of the most common productivity software skills requested by UK employers. With the highest number of job adverts of 810,239, a high advertised salary of \u00a331,300 and a versatility of 0.98 (very high), Microsoft Excel has a projected growth rate of 23% in the next 5 years.<\/p>\n<p>In the US too, millions of jobs require you to have Excel skills. A <a href=\"https:\/\/www.burning-glass.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/Digital_Edge_report_2017_final.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">research by Burning Glass Technologies and Capital One<\/a> has found that having digital skills leads to better employment and higher income. In fact, the impact is actually more not on sophisticated skills such as writing code but on using software such as spreadsheets.<\/p>\n<p>Different jobs demand different levels of Excel proficiency. Be it simple data manipulation, core financial calculations, or advanced subskills of Excel such as VBA and pivot tables, Excel finds its way into just about every job aspect. Regardless, fluency in Excel makes you more versatile and is definitely a plus for your career.<\/p>\n<h3>What is my experience with Excel?<\/h3>\n<p>I am a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.coursera.org\/instructor\/archisha-bhar\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Guided Project Instructor<\/a> at Coursera, my first Guided Project being <a href=\"https:\/\/www.coursera.org\/projects\/problem-solving-using-microsoft-excel\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Problem Solving using Microsoft Excel<\/a> (currently unavailable). I am also a Beta Tester at Coursera, having tested many courses before they\u2019re officially launched (including one in this list).<\/p>\n<p>I have taken <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/@archisha\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">over 50 online courses<\/a> in various subjects. My experience as an online learner and teacher has given me some perspective on what to look for in an online course. I used my experience to evaluate each course in this list.<\/p>\n<h2><a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-79248\" src=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/Class-Central-Preview-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"512\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/Class-Central-Preview-2.png 1024w, https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/Class-Central-Preview-2-300x150.png 300w, https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/03\/Class-Central-Preview-2-768x384.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/a><\/h2>\n<h2>Course Ranking Methodology<\/h2>\n<p>I built this ranking following the now tried-and-tested methodology I used in previous rankings (<a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/category\/best-courses\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">you can find them all here<\/a>). It involves a three-step process:<\/p>\n<ol>\n<li aria-level=\"1\"><b>Research:<\/b> I started by leveraging Class Central\u2019s database with <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/subjects\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">100K+ online courses<\/a> and 200K reviews. Then, I made a preliminary selection of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/subject\/microsoft-excel\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">900+ Microsoft Excel courses<\/a> by rating, reviews, and bookmarks.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\"><b>Evaluate:<\/b> I read through reviews on Class Central, Reddit, and course providers to understand what other learners thought about each course and combined it with my own experience as a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/@archisha\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">learner<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\"><b>Select:<\/b> Well-made courses were picked if they presented valuable and engaging content and they have to fit in a set of criteria and be ranked accordingly: comprehensive curriculum, release date, affordability, ratings and enrollments.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n<p>The end result is a unique selection of courses that combines a decade of Class Central data and my own experience as an online learner to try to get the best of both worlds. So far, I\u2019ve spent more than 11 hours building this list, and I\u2019ll continue to update it.<\/p>\n<h2>Course Ranking Statistics<\/h2>\n<p>Here are some statistics regarding this course ranking:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">Combined, these courses have accrued over <b>1.2M<\/b> enrollments.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">Nine courses are <b>free<\/b> or <b>free-to-audit<\/b> and one course is <b>paid<\/b>.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">The most-represented course provider in the ranking is <b>Coursera<\/b>, with six courses.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">Nine courses are in <b>English<\/b> and one course is in <b>Spanish<\/b>.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">Combined, these courses have been bookmarked over <b>10,584<\/b> times on Class Central, while the Microsoft Excel subject itself has been bookmarked over <b>15,871<\/b> times.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">Combined, these courses have received over <b>500<\/b> reviews on Class Central.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>So without further ado, let\u2019s get to my picks for the best Microsoft Excel online courses.<\/p>\n<h2 id=\"anchor-1\">1. <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/excel-essentials-9638\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Excel Skills for Business: Essentials (Macquarie University)<\/a><\/h2>\n<figure id=\"attachment_80332\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-80332\" style=\"width: 1024px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"wp-image-80332 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/1.-Excel-Skills-for-Business_-Essentials-Macquarie.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"512\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/1.-Excel-Skills-for-Business_-Essentials-Macquarie.png 1024w, https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/1.-Excel-Skills-for-Business_-Essentials-Macquarie-300x150.png 300w, https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/1.-Excel-Skills-for-Business_-Essentials-Macquarie-768x384.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-80332\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Prashan S. M. Karunaratne (left) and Nicky Bull (right), co-instructors of the course<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>My #1 pick for the best Microsoft Excel online course is the <b>free-to-audit<\/b> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/excel-essentials-9638\"><i>Excel Skills for Business: Essentials<\/i><\/a>, offered by Macquarie University on Coursera.<\/p>\n<p>The course is made keeping the beginners in mind. With its excellent course structure, high-quality videos, detailed explanations, impressive readings, and ample practice opportunities, this course easily makes it to the top of this list.<\/p>\n<p>At every step, the instructors will be there to remind you that in order to build a strong foundation, you must practice thoroughly. There are practice opportunities at every step of the course. And to make the process more fun, they will take you through Sean\u2019s Excel journey. Who\u2019s Sean? Well, it could be you!<\/p>\n<p>This unique storytelling way of teaching makes your learning more personalized. Though originally intended for business, this course will teach you the building blocks that are applicable to any scenario. So, don\u2019t be scared by the course\u2019s name if you don\u2019t come from a business background!<\/p>\n<h3>What You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>The course starts with the basics of the Excel user interface and terminology, including selecting and navigating data using shortcuts and tools. From there, you&#8217;ll move on to perform data entry, editing, and deleting, which are often overlooked but essential skills to have. This course will give you a better understanding of the different data types and how to work with them.<\/p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll dive into Excel formulas and functions, which are powerful tools that allow you to perform various tasks quickly. You&#8217;ll learn how to write syntactically correct functions and perform simple calculations with cell referencing and the order of operations. You&#8217;ll also learn how to format your spreadsheet, including font formatting, bordering cells, aligning data, and changing number types. You&#8217;ll also learn how to work with data in Excel, including finding, replacing, sorting, filtering data, and highlighting specific data with Conditional Formatting.<\/p>\n<p>Finally, you&#8217;ll end the course by creating graphs and charts in Excel. You&#8217;ll learn how to modify and style your graphs and charts to make them more attractive and effective. This section will help you visualize your data in a way that&#8217;s clear and easy to understand. By the end of this course, you&#8217;ll have all the skills you need to manage data, perform calculations, and visualize information in Excel.<\/p>\n<h3>How You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>The course is broken down into 6 weeks. Each week involves about 3 to 4 hours of work. Concepts are taught through a combination of videos and a lot of practice exercises.<\/p>\n<p>Remember Sean? Each week, you\u2019ll be presented with a challenge Sean faces with Excel. The instructors, Nicky and Prashan, will sit together to discuss Sean\u2019s problems in depth. This will be a great opportunity for you to gain deeper insight into each week\u2019s topic.<\/p>\n<p>Lessons are taught in the form of practice videos. Practice makes permanent! That\u2019s why, after each video, there\u2019s an ungraded practice quiz to test your understanding. And that\u2019s not all! At the end of each week, there are practice challenges in the form of Excel files where you\u2019ll work on finding the solutions in Excel itself.<\/p>\n<p>Finally, there are graded quizzes at the end of each week that will contribute towards your final score in this course.<\/p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Institution<\/td>\n<td>Macquarie University<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Provider<\/td>\n<td>Coursera<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Instructor<\/td>\n<td>Prashan S. M. Karunaratne, Nicky Bull, Yvonne Breyer<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Level<\/td>\n<td>Beginner<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Workload<\/td>\n<td>26 hours<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enrollments<\/td>\n<td>686K<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rating<\/td>\n<td>4.9\/5.0 (42K)<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Certificate<\/td>\n<td>Paid<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<\/tbody>\n<\/table>\n<h3>Fun Facts<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">This course is part of the highly acclaimed <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/excel-data-analytics-visualization-35061\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Excel Skills for Data Analytics and Visualization Specialization<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">It has been bookmarked 2.8K times on Class Central!<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">This course has been utilized by international organizations such as the UNDP, UNICEF.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">It has also been translated into Arabic by the Government of the UAE.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\"><a href=\"https:\/\/researchers.mq.edu.au\/en\/persons\/prashan-karunaratne?msclkid=8f98d97ac5e511ecb7f726b1c22e7a3e\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Prashan<\/a> is an award-winning lecturer who is well-known for his catchphrase, \u201cEveryone, say wow!\u201d.<\/li>\n<li aria-level=\"1\">Even though Nicky is a computer programmer and analyst, she has a second bachelor\u2019s degree in English Literature!<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>If you\u2019re interested in this course, you can find <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/excel-essentials-9638\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">more information about the course and how to enroll here<\/a>.<\/p>\n<h2 id=\"anchor-2\">2. <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/everyday-excel-part-1-19327\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Everyday Excel, Part 1 (University of Colorado Boulder)<\/a><\/h2>\n<figure id=\"attachment_80331\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-80331\" style=\"width: 1024px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"wp-image-80331 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/2.-Everyday-Excel-Part-1-University-of-Colorado-Boulder.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"512\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/2.-Everyday-Excel-Part-1-University-of-Colorado-Boulder.png 1024w, https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/2.-Everyday-Excel-Part-1-University-of-Colorado-Boulder-300x150.png 300w, https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/report\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/05\/2.-Everyday-Excel-Part-1-University-of-Colorado-Boulder-768x384.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-80331\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Charlie Nuttelman, instructor of the course<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<p>My second pick for the best Microsoft Excel online course is the <b>free-to-audit<\/b> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/everyday-excel-part-1-19327\"><i>Everyday Excel, Part 1<\/i><\/a>, offered by the University of Colorado Boulder on Coursera.<\/p>\n<p>This course is one of my personal favorites since this was the first course I ever took on Excel. I instantly became a fan of the instructor\u2019s teaching style, and proceeded to take his next two courses, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/everyday-excel-part-2-19571\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Everyday Excel, Part 2<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/www.classcentral.com\/course\/everyday-excel-projects-33463\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Everyday Excel, Part 3 (Projects)<\/a>. So if you\u2019re looking for an interactive instructor, you should definitely check this one out!<\/p>\n<p>Many Excel courses use complex examples with large volumes of complex financial or scientific data that many of us might not be familiar with. But Charlie Nuttelman uses very simple and goofy examples to grab the learner\u2019s attention. Even if he ever uses technical examples, he makes sure that the focus is on Excel and not on the subject.<\/p>\n<p>As a civil engineering student, I find it really thoughtful that he, as an engineer himself, emphasizes on the utility of Excel in this field. This is often overlooked in many courses, so it\u2019s definitely a thumbs-up from me!<\/p>\n<h3>What You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>You&#8217;ll start by learning the fundamentals of Excel. You&#8217;ll learn how to save and open files, navigate through worksheets using shortcuts, and understand the difference between cells, columns, and rows. You&#8217;ll also learn about cell formatting, conditional formatting, autofill, and fill series. We&#8217;ll teach you how to name cells and cell ranges, and introduce you to basic macro recording using VBA.<\/p>\n<p>Moving on, you&#8217;ll learn how to input mathematical formulas, and we&#8217;ll cover Excel&#8217;s syntax and order of operations. You&#8217;ll also learn how to troubleshoot by looking for errors and fixing them when you don&#8217;t get the expected result.<\/p>\n<p>Then, you&#8217;ll delve deeper into Excel functions. We&#8217;ll cover logical functions such as IF, AND, and OR, as well as advanced logical functions such as SUMIF, COUNTIF, and AVERAGEIF. You&#8217;ll also learn how to overcome limitations of autofill using text functions, and create your own user-defined function in VBA.<\/p>\n<p>After that, you&#8217;ll focus on data management in Excel. You&#8217;ll learn how to apply filters, create Excel tables, validate data, sort data, remove duplicates, and consolidate data from multiple sources. You&#8217;ll also get to learn one-way lookup functions such as VLOOKUP, INDEX, and MATCH.<\/p>\n<p>Finally, you&#8217;ll learn how to present your data in the form of graphs and charts using data visualization in Excel. We&#8217;ll cover scatter plots, column charts, and pie charts, as well as other ways to visualize data such as pivot tables, slicers, and sparklines. You&#8217;ll also learn how to share Excel&#8217;s data with Word and PowerPoint, print your worksheets, and convert them to .pdf documents.<\/p>\n<h3>How You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>The course is broken down into 5 weeks. Each week involves about 4 to 5 hours of work. Concepts are taught through dozens of short videos.<\/p>\n<p>Charlie Nuttelman calls his videos \u201cscreencasts\u201d. These are demos that give step-by-step instructions on each topic. You can work alongside him by downloading the workbooks provided in the course. The explanations are easy to follow, and there are ungraded in-video quizzes (quizzes within the video) to check your understanding too.<\/p>\n<p>The quizzes in this course are somewhat unique. There are two types of graded quizzes in each week \u2013 the usual quizzes and the in-application assignments. For the latter one, you\u2019ll get an Excel file where you\u2019ll solve the problem on your own computer, and once you\u2019ve successfully found the solution, you\u2019ll get a \u201ccompletion code\u201d that you\u2019ll put into the quiz.<\/p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Institution<\/td>\n<td>University of Colorado Boulder<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Provider<\/td>\n<td>Coursera<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Instructor<\/td>\n<td>Charlie Nuttelman<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Level<\/td>\n<td>Beginner<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Workload<\/td>\n<td>25 hours<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enrollments<\/td>\n<td>172K<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rating<\/td>\n<td>4.7\/5.0 (2.5K)<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Certificate<\/td>\n<td>Paid<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<\/tbody>\n<\/table>\n<h3>Fun Facts<\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li aria