u with essential Excel skills so that you can succeed in any organization.<\/p>\n<p>Along with teaching the basic concepts of Excel, this course will also give you a foundational understanding of business data analysis. That\u2019s why, most of the examples used in this course are finance-related. But you can still learn the foundations of Excel since the concepts remain the same across all fields.<\/p>\n<h3>What You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>In Week 1, you\u2019ll learn about the key foundational features of Excel. These include the Excel user interface, basic Excel terminology, and performing data entry in Excel.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll understand Excel formulas work, and how to incorporate cell and cell ranges within formulas. You\u2019ll also be able to develop your own formulas in Excel using mathematical expressions with a single arithmetic operator.<\/p>\n<p>In Week 2, you\u2019ll be introduced to Excel functions. Functions are a vital part of Excel. Almost every kind of work in Excel requires functions. And it\u2019s equally important to know the syntax of Excel functions in order to apply them effectively.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll learn how to write functions in Excel, use them to perform calculations, and understand the different cell references in order to use them in formulas and functions.<\/p>\n<p>Week 3 is all about formatting your worksheets. Changing the style of your layout can greatly improve the readability and presentation of your work, and also make it easier to use.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll learn how to use formatting tools such as font formatting, alignment, number formatting, and styles to highlight certain elements in your worksheet and make your data more presentable.<\/p>\n<p>Week 4 will teach you how to work with data in Excel. You\u2019ll learn how to manage your spreadsheets, which includes finding required data using Filter and Sort, retrieving and changing existing data into some other data using Find and Replace, and using Conditional Formatting to highlight specific data in your worksheet that require attention.<\/p>\n<p>In Week 5, you\u2019ll take a look at visualizing your data using graphs and charts. It is often easier to interpret an illustration instead of a bunch of boring data.<\/p>\n<p>Representing your data graphically enhances the quality of your work and also draws the user\u2019s attention. You\u2019ll learn about the different options Excel provides for creating attractive graphs and charts to visualize comparisons and trends.<\/p>\n<p>Finally, in Week 6, you\u2019ll end the course by learning all about how to print your worksheets in Excel so that you can share data offline. Printing worksheets in Excel can be a tricky job, but adjusting its layout properly can give great results.<\/p>\n<p>That\u2019s why, you\u2019ll learn how to optimize your spreadsheet for printing by altering print settings such as margins, orientation, headers and footers before finally printing it.<\/p>\n<h3>How You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>The course is broken down into 6 weeks. Each week involves about 4 to 6 hours of work. Concepts are taught through a number of short videos and practice challenges.<\/p>\n<p>Videos are short and interactive, and concepts are taught through real-world problems. All the workbooks are provided so that you can work along. The examples used are mostly financial, but that\u2019s not a limitation. Even if you come from a different background, you can still learn Excel since the fundamentals remain the same.<\/p>\n<p>As for assessments, there is a practice challenge and a graded assignment after every two weeks. For the practice challenges, you\u2019ll need to download the Excel files provided and go through the instructions to solve the problems on your own computer.<\/p>\n<p>At the end of the course, there\u2019s a final assessment where you\u2019ll have to apply all that you\u2019ve learned throughout the course.<\/p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Institution<\/td>\n<td>The University of