important in many fields of work. By using a good prediction model, you can tell what your future sales will be, for example. Spreadsheets are a powerful tool in this matter. In spreadsheets, you can not only perform simple calculations and data visualizations, but can also build powerful forecasting models.<\/p>\n<p>If you\u2019ve already seen or have access to Excel, it won\u2019t be difficult for you to actually build these models by yourself. This course will guide you through that process by first giving you an introduction to basic spreadsheet tools and formulas. Once you\u2019ve mastered that, you\u2019ll see how you can actually use Excel to predict future data.<\/p>\n<h3>What You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>Week 1 is all about the basics of spreadsheets. You\u2019ll first get an overview of the history of spreadsheets. You\u2019ll learn about their basic capabilities, and how you can create models with them.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll be able to navigate through a spreadsheet, understand different data types used in spreadsheets, spreadsheet notations for mathematical operations, and use built-in formulas and functions in spreadsheets. Other than that, you\u2019ll be able to write your own simple formulas, and troubleshoot common errors.<\/p>\n<p>In Week 2, you\u2019ll move from spreadsheet to model. You\u2019ll start off by organizing and laying out model elements, and learn about the types of objective functions and their use.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll then take a look at the highly-used what-if analysis, sensitivity analysis, and other classic models such as basic cash flow models, sensitivity analysis, linear programming models and deterministic models. By creating assumptions, decision variables, and outcomes, you\u2019ll be able to create\u00a0 your own models that reflect real-world events.<\/p>\n<p>Week 3 deals with uncertainty and probability calculations using spreadsheets. You&#8217;ll learn about random variables, probability distributions, and power, exponential and log functions in model formulas.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll also learn how to measure correlations between variables using spreadsheet statistical functions, and understand the results of functions that calculate correlations. You\u2019ll then take a look at\u00a0 models for calculating probability trees and decision trees, as well as use regression tools to make predictions.<\/p>\n<p>Finally, in Week 4, you\u2019ll learn about Monte Carlo simulations and linear programs in spreadsheets. These are models widely used for simulation and optimization of real-world scenarios.<\/p>\n<p>You\u2019ll see how you can run Monte Carlo simulations in spreadsheets, understand the different types of problems you can solve with linear programs, and implement\u00a0 all this in spreadsheets. You\u2019ll learn to model uncertainty and risk, use Excel\u2019s solver tool for optimization, and take a look at the differences between Excel and Sheets.<\/p>\n<h3>How You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>The course is broken down into 4 weeks. Each week involves about 1 to 2 hours of work. Concepts are taught through a combination of videos and readings.<\/p>\n<p>The video lectures are moderately short, giving hands-on demonstrations on solving real-world problems in Excel. The readings consist of lecture slides, Excel files of the examples shown in the videos, and external links to useful resources.<\/p>\n<p>At the end of each week, there\u2019s a graded quiz to test your understanding.<\/p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Institution<\/td>\n<td>University of Pennsylvania<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Provider<\/td>\n<td>Coursera<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Instructor<\/td>\n<td>Don Huesman<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Level<\/td>\n<td>Mixed<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Workload<\/td>\n<td>26 hours<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Enrollments<\/td>\n<td>96K<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rating<\/td>\n<td>4.2\/5.0 (3.5K)<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Certificate<\/td>\n<td>Paid<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<\/tbody>\n<\/table>\n<h3>One Thing to Not