e fundamentals of Excel is overlooked and considered too basic.<\/p>\n<p>\u201c<i>But if we don&#8217;t master these aspects of Excel, it&#8217;s going to make our learning later on much more difficult and frankly, much less effective.<\/i>\u201d<\/p>\n<p>I completely agree with him, and this is true for learning anything for that matter. That\u2019s why, in this course, he will take you through the basics of Excel so that you are much more comfortable with Excel than you imagined. Later on, you\u2019ll be able to build more advanced Excel skills upon this foundation in future.<\/p>\n<h3>What You\u2019ll Learn<\/h3>\n<p>Week 1 is all about the absolute basics of Excel. You\u2019ll start from the ground up by learning how to open Excel on your computer, and familiarizing yourself with the Excel layout and interface. You\u2019ll also learn basic Excel terminology, and understand how spreadsheets are organized.<\/p>\n<p>Then you\u2019ll move on to the different data types Excel can handle and learn to format cells correctly. You\u2019ll also learn how to enter data in Excel, and explore some useful shortcuts that will help you perform common tasks efficiently.<\/p>\n<p>In Week 2, you\u2019ll learn how to visualize data in the form of charts. plots and graphs. It\u2019s often easier and more appealing to interpret trends and comparisons visually rather than quantitatively.<\/p>\n<p>So here you\u2019ll learn some of the common types of graphs and charts such as bar charts, scatterplots, pie and stacked column charts, and also combine different different plot types according to your needs.<\/p>\n<p>In Week 3, you\u2019ll move on to Excel formulas and functions. You\u2019ll see how you can summarize your data by calculating sums, counts, and averages using simple Excel functions.<\/p>\n<p>Then you\u2019ll learn about cell referencing in Excel which includes relative and absolute references. These are used in Excel formulas and functions to tell Excel which cells to work on